People adapt to fit in and be accepted. To escape rejection and social ostracism, people typically adopt a group's views, attitudes, and habits. Authorities also impact conformity. In order to please or escape punishment, people may follow the views and actions of those in power. The urge to belong to a group is constant regardless of knowledge uncertainty. Group size: Larger groups put greater pressure on members to comply. Unanimity: Perceived consensus enhances the urge to comply. Public vs. private reactions: Public responses put greater pressure on people to comply. 